snippet.textDisplay: I don't understand why governments don't just invest a massive amount of money into infrastructure projects. Infrastructure projects are the surest way to economic growth. Not only do you provide jobs for construction workers, but also those construction workers will then spend in that community thus recirculating that wealth, you recapture much of that money back in payroll taxes, those construction workers get more experience so they become more efficient, and we save money on welfare and social safety nets for these workers. The infrastructure itself provides jobs and it becomes an asset. In the case of mass transit we also save people many hours of commuting time and brain fatigue and we decrease traffic congestion. This should be a no brainer and yet Americans continue to shove money down the throats of the military industrial complex like their lives depended on it.

When I was a young lad, I wanted to be an architect but after growing up and a tour in the Army (to man me up) I stumbled into the engineering side of building and fell in love with it. I've had a fantastic career and journey. Made good $$$ (not at first), Traveled all over, Made many friends that have come and gone. I've been fired for refusing to short cut a task or challenging safety conflicts.  (a rarity) If your gonna build things people live, travel or work in do it right. I get pissed when I hear about a failure that was caused by greed, carelessness, or as in most cases trying to meet schedule! Good luck and stay safe to all current and future engineers!!!  And everybody else as well!

snippet.textDisplay:
It’s always awesome to see public transportation projects take hold. As much as I love cars and as much as I love driving, money spent on public transport helps the roads too, because it gives more people less reasons to drive, freeing up the roads and doing no end of good to the environment and road safety. Road expansion is nowhere near as sustainable as public transport expansion is, and I’d love to see more of it here in Australia.

I feel really horrible for what people in the US have to put up with, but they dug their own grave in that regard. Public transport used to be awesome in the US until automakers bought and shut down light rail lines everywhere and replaced the systems with buses that they made, and forced more people into cars that they also made. The sooner the US auto industry dies, the better off the country will be because they can start actually rebuilding public transport again.
